-- South African Yellow Corn Advances for Eighth Session in a Row
-- B y   T s h e p i s o   M o k h e m a
-- 2013-10-23T13:13:53Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-10-23/south-african-yellow-corn-advances-for-eighth-session-in-a-row.html
Yellow-corn futures traded in  South
Africa  rose for an eighth straight session, extending the
longest streak of advances in more than five years.  The grain for delivery in December climbed 1.5 percent to
2,228 rand ($228) a metric ton by the close today on the South
African Futures Exchange. The run of increases is the lengthiest
since June 2008 for a most-active contract, data compiled by
Bloomberg showed. White corn for the same delivery month gained
0.5 percent to 2,397 rand a ton.  South Africa is the continentâ€™s biggest corn producer. A
meal made from white corn is a staple food in the nation and the
yellow variety is mostly fed to animals.  Wheat for delivery in December increased 0.5 percent to
3,499 rand a ton. Soybeans for the same delivery month added 0.9
percent to 5,685 rand a ton.  To contact the reporter on this story:
